**Why should this rule be included in ESLint (instead of a plugin)?**

Rejecting a Promise with a non-error is a bad practice, and is generally applicable regardless of what the Promises are being used for. We already have the [`no-throw-literal`](http://eslint.org/docs/rules/no-throw-literal) rule, which enforces the same thing with synchronous errors. This rule would complement `no-throw-literal` for async errors (i.e. Promise rejections).

Some Promise libraries, such as [bluebird](http://bluebirdjs.com/docs/warning-explanations.html#warning-a-promise-was-rejected-with-a-non-error), enforce this with a warning at runtime.

